To clear up any Qs: Yes, we will continue to respect any method of on-chain enforcement – including the operator filter – on new and existing collections. 

For collections that do not have on-chain enforcement, creator earnings will be optional with a minimum of 0.5% applied.

@LooksRare The requirements are simply that you honor creator earnings for collections that have chosen on-chain enforcement. We hope you’ll join us. 

More details here: https://t.co/i0PMdt5HiV
12/ Stay tuned for more info, as we continue exploring ways to reward our most loyal users.

11/ This is the start of a new era for OpenSea. We’re excited to test this model and find the right balance of incentives and motivations for all ecosystem participants – creators, collectors, and power buyers and sellers.

10/ Third – We’re updating the operator filter to allow sales using NFT marketplaces with the same policies (including Blur, as they make good on their promise). 
Now, creators won’t have to make the false choice between receiving earnings on OpenSea or Blur.
9/ Second – We’re moving to a minimum 0.5% creator earnings model, with the option for sellers to pay more. This applies to all collections that do not use on-chain enforcement (old and new).
8/ First and foremost – We’re dropping our OpenSea fee to 0% for a promotional period of time.
7/ While we continue to uphold on-chain enforcement through the operator filter, we’re moving to a different fee structure that reflects the needs of today’s ecosystem.

6/ Today, ~80% of total ecosystem volume does not pay full creator earnings, and the majority of volume (even accounting for inorganic activity) has moved to a zero-fee environment.

Source: https://t.co/8tLN035cGp

This requires a change.

5/ Recent events – including Blur’s decision to roll back creator earnings (even on filtered collections) and the false choice they’re forcing creators to make between liquidity on Blur or OpenSea – prove that our attempts are not working.
4/ We thought we could catalyze widespread enforcement of creator earnings, and we hoped others might come up with more resilient solutions – this hasn’t happened.

3/ We’ve worked to defend creator earnings on ALL collections when others didn’t.  And when we introduced the Operator Filter, it was our belief that on-chain enforcement was the best way for creators to secure their revenue stream from the ongoing resale of their work.

2/ Context: There’s been a massive shift in the NFT ecosystem. 

In October, we started to see meaningful volume and users move to NFT marketplaces that don’t fully enforce creator earnings. 

Today, that shift has accelerated dramatically despite our best efforts.

We’re making some big changes today:
1) OpenSea fee → 0% for a limited time
2) Moving to optional creator earnings (0.5% min) for all collections without on-chain enforcement (old & new)
3) Marketplaces with the same policies will not be blocked by the operator filter

4/ We’re excited to keep evolving the language we use on our platform and we’re grateful for the ongoing dialogue with the community! 

Let us know how you feel about this change!

3/ Why not call them “royalties?” Fair question. You can read our full explanation below 👇
TLDR: the word “royalties” has different meanings in various contexts, and isn’t applicable to all types of NFTs.
https://t.co/J9MhCKv8kz

2/ There are a couple important notes as we make this change:
- We still believe there’s a more accurate classification than “royalties”
- “Creator earnings” in this context doesn’t include creator revenue from the initial sale

In speaking with a number of creators, we heard time and time again that the term “Creator Fees” doesn’t fully reflect their impact and true nature.

Starting today, we will exclusively call “creator fees” → “creator earnings” 🧵

18/ Lastly, in order to enforce a more consistent, on-chain standard for creator fees, we’ve amended the operator filter’s policies to require that contracts deployed after January 2nd implement EIP 2981 as their objective source of truth for creator fee preferences.
17/ To that end, starting January 2nd, 2023, creators that opt out of on-chain creator fee enforcement will be able to set creator fees that are optional for collectors to comply with.
16/ Additionally, we’ve heard compelling pushback from creators on the lack of an alternative mechanism for earning creator fees on OpenSea outside of leveraging our enforcement tool.

15/ We heard the feedback loud and clear that this window of time was not sufficient, so we’ve extended the deadline for when new collections will be required to comply with the creator fee enforcement standard to January 2nd, 2023 across all EVM chains.
14/ Many creators leverage tools such as @manifoldxyz to deploy collections — and those tools needed more time to adjust to our new policy.
13/ Initially, collections launched after November 8th were required to implement filtering of creator fee-evading marketplaces in order to set enforced creator fees on OpenSea…
12/ As part of this change, we’ve made a few adjustments to OpenSea’s creator fees policy to accommodate feedback we’ve heard over the past month. More on that below ⬇️
11/The next steps will be hard, but they're critical. We need your help — so come join the conversation: https://t.co/tHVo7wMk19

10/ We’re glad to join in this effort with our colleagues across the industry. We also emphatically welcome @blur_io, @looksrare, and @sudoswap to revert their stances on creator fee avoidance and join the conversation as members of CORI.

9/ Our hope is that bringing the conversation into a more public and inclusive forum can reduce the thrash industry players have experienced, and can build more community buy-in for the space’s evolving standards around creator fees.

8/ Our number one goal is to incentivize a shift in the industry back towards respecting creator fees universally — so that on-chain enforcement tools can become an option for some, but not a requirement for all.

7/ This has been a very hard month for the community, and we acknowledge that at times the choices we made were hasty and unaccommodating to some creators’ needs. There are ultimately no perfect solutions to the industry’s drift away from respecting creator fees.

6/ We’re proud to partner with the group originally behind https://t.co/0SEGmsYTOp to spearhead the initial governance of the registry. Soon, we’ll be expanding governance of the registry to include more stakeholders, including — critically — voices in the creator community.

5/ The charter of CORI is to create a decentralized body tasked with:
- Open, transparent governance of the existing Operator Filter registry and the policies that surround it
- “Built in public” R&D focused on improving mechanisms for creator fee enforcement in the future

4/ The tool is very much a v1, and we acknowledge that there are flaws that need to be addressed as we iterate further. 

Our first step towards a better v2 is to decentralize management and governance of the registry — initially, by granting control of it to CORI.
3/ It’s an existential imperative for the space to preserve creator fees. Recently, OpenSea took a step intended to protect them by releasing an on-chain enforcement tool called the Operator Filter.

2/ The revolutionary potential of creator fees has been under attack for months. Marketplaces that do not respect creator fees have been rapidly growing in prominence, and creators, in turn, have seen their effective creator fees severely diminished.

Before Jan 2nd, OpenSea will transfer ownership of the Operator Filter Registry to a multi-sig controlled by a collective incl. @ourzora @manifoldxyz @foundation @superrare @niftygateway & @opensea.

Meet the Creator Ownership Research Institute (CORI) https://t.co/sT8G3A59zk 🧵

5/ We see no need to alter current standard practices on these chains. At the same time, we DO want to ensure that creator fees are future-proofed against any future fee-evasion. We hope this is helpful!

3/ Our policy is that creator fees will be enforced for *all* projects that launch on these chains before Jan 2, 2023.

5/ Since some of you have said term is misleading we wanted to address this, but we’d love to hear alternatives too: how do YOU think we should refer to creator fees? 🤔
4/ We started using “creator fees” and “creator earnings” long before this debate as a more neutral (thus, safer) descriptive alternative term for royalties.
3/ For example, in some cases, creators indicated that royalties implied licensing of their content and not simply support for their work. It doesn’t have as uniform a meaning as many assume.
2/ Basically, the word “royalties” has specific--but differing--meanings in various contexts and the term isn’t even applicable to all types of NFTs.
A lot of you have been asking why we keep calling "royalties" "creator fees." The answer is honestly a little boring, but we wanted to address it! 🧵⬇️

15/ We’re in this with you, but this fight will take more than just words. It’s time for action.

14/ Beyond all of this, we plan to share more creator-focused tech/tooling updates we're excited about later this week; also @dfinzer and @AnnieFauv will be on @overpricedjpegs this Friday to talk about the future of creator fees on OpenSea.
13/ We will start open sourcing our data on creator fees in the upcoming weeks for everyone to use. In the meantime, we encourage you to check out @punk9059’s tweets on this topic.

12/ In short, we’re at a collective inflection point: if everyone left in this ecosystem who believes that creator fees are important to our future links arms on this, we WILL ensure that fees are durable.

11/ And collectors, you can choose platforms that honor creator fees even if it means being OK with paying more for NFTs on fee-enforcing marketplaces. Creators can build incentives and on-chain enforcement, but it won’t mean anything if you don’t show up for them.

10/ A REMINDER: in order to recognize creator fees for *new* collections, you must adopt on-chain enforcement tools. Our new registry is one such tool, but there are others, and we support those as well.
…3) You can refuse to link to fee-avoiding marketplaces from your project websites.
…2) You can develop more incentives for your communities to continue to pay fees (and we can show these in our product)...
9/ Creators - there are immediate steps you can take: For existing collections 1) You can build paths to on-chain enforcement for your existing collections (we’re here to help)...
8/ We’re awed by the passion we’ve seen from creators and collectors alike this week. We were looking for your feedback, and we heard it, loud and clear. Now let’s discuss what comes next.
7/ Unless something changes soon, this space is trending toward significantly fewer fees paid to creators. No policy that we implement will reverse this trend if this behavior continues.
6/ Simply put, in the last week, almost half of the creator fees set by the top 20 collections were ignored. This amounts to well over $1M for creators left on the table.
5/ This isn’t theoretical, it’s happening now, and the trend is accelerating. Here’s the data: https://t.co/Tzi4QPd9dc

4/ For collectors, this means NFTs they really want are increasingly likely to be listed on marketplaces that don't enforce creator fees. Even if these collectors *say* they want to pay creator fees, they're becoming more and more prone to buying on those marketplaces.

3/ One observation: in the economic downturn, many of those looking to sell their NFTs are trying to sell them for as much as they can. Moving their listings to marketplaces that don’t enforce fees is one way to do this.

2/ When we began seeking guidance from our community, it was to understand a range of perspectives (from creators, collectors, and builders in this space) that would help us make sense of trends and behaviors we were observing.

UPDATE: We will continue to enforce creator fees on all existing collections.

We’ve been listening to you in Spaces, 1:1 conversations, and in the comments. We really appreciate you sharing your perspectives, making time for conversations, and showing your passionate support for creators.
We hope many creators will use our tool and others to take control of their business model. And we hope more marketplaces choose to enforce fees as a default in the future.

Of course, creators can choose not to use any tool, and their items can be bought and sold on *any* marketplace - in those cases, however, OpenSea will not enforce their fees. We want to be super clear about this.

Hey all! Something we want to be clear about: yes, we're building a tool that allows creators to enforce fees on chain but no one *has* to use it. Creators can use a different tool that prevents their NFTs from being bought and sold on marketplaces that don't enforce creator fees

For us our focus is on building tools that empower creators. We can't demand that other marketplaces invest in the protection of creator fees, but we can optimize our platform to serve as much of the community as possible.

9/ There is SO MUCH more to discuss when it comes to a topic this important. We know it's long, but we tried to include as much valuable information as possible around our thought process and open questions here: https://t.co/wK3Yp4dyto
8/ We recognize not all creators, collections, and communities are the same and we are looking to create a long-term policy that reflects that.

7/ In transparency, the consideration set for what happens after Dec 8 is wide open – w/ options ranging from continuing to enforce off-chain fees for some subsets of collections to allowing optional creator fees to collaborating on other on-chain enforcement options for creators

6/ Knowing how difficult it is to enforce fees on-chain for existing collections, we won’t make any changes for existing collections until at least Dec 8, 2022. In the meantime, we'll hold conversations w/ our communities to get their POV on a more optimal outcome
5/ We recognize this is a first step that addresses new collections, but we also know how important it is to think about alternatives to help existing collections navigate this new ecosystem dynamic.

4/ This tool is our first version of on-chain enforcement, and in the coming months we’ll launch additional tools and improvements for on-chain enforcement of new collections, and we’ll engage with the community to get feedback on them along the way.

3/ To that end today we’re launching a tool for on-chain enforcement of creator fees for *new collections*  Starting 12pm ET on Tuesday Nov 8 OpenSea will enforce creator fees only for new collections that use an on-chain enforcement tool such as this one. https://t.co/i0PMdt5HiV

2/ It’s clear that many creators want the ability to enforce fees on-chain & we believe that choice should be theirs–not a marketplace’s–to make.  

So we’re building tools we hope will balance the scales by putting more power in creators’ hands to control their business model.

There’s been a lot of discussion over the past few months about business models for NFT creators & whether creator fees (“royalties”) are viable. 

Given our role in the ecosystem, we want to take a thoughtful, principled approach to this topic & to lead w/ solutions. 🧵

8/ You can read more about our efforts to make this space safer here: https://t.co/AISOSMLVqK

7/ While malicious URL and theft detection can help reduce theft-related issues on OpenSea, we know this problem requires ecosystem-level solutions. That’s why we’re working with marketplaces, wallet providers, and others to develop a holistic scam detection and prevention system

6/ Items involved in detected suspicious behavior will be temporarily disabled on OpenSea, and the previous owner will immediately be notified via email. The previous owner can then share feedback with us to reinstate the item and enable it to be sold again.
5/ Today, via a new pilot program, we’re beginning to test a new system to try to detect NFT theft in REAL-TIME and prevent further resales of suspected stolen items to unsuspecting buyers.

4/ Theft Detection and Disablement 🔐

Until now, we needed theft victims to file reports to have stolen items flagged on OpenSea. Unfortunately, thieves often resold those items to unsuspecting buyers before any action could be taken.

3/ But since suspicious behaviors often show up on OpenSea before they are known to be bad, the system goes a step further by analyzing interactions and transactions to identify malicious behaviors like signature farming and wallet draining 🔎

2/ Malicious URL Detection and Removal 🚫

We just launched a new system that proactively scans URLs shared on OpenSea to identify if they may be malicious. It starts by cross checking a given URL against a blocklist of known malicious sites.

1/ Stolen items and scams are big issues in the NFT space. So, we’ve been hard at work on 2 new solutions to address both on OpenSea: 

Introducing Malicious URL Detection and Removal 🚫 and Theft Detection and Disablement 🔐

6/ We continue to believe creators should have autonomy, so they’ll of course be able to toggle off OpenRarity for their collections if they want.

We know that this is a big decision, so it’s important the community fully understands why we have so much faith in @openrarity.

5/ As a result of this decision, we know that some collectors will see rarity rankings appear for their collections. But, we think increased awareness and continued adoption will be a net-positive & reduce needless friction for buyers & sellers.

4/ We’re proud of this decision and don’t take it lightly.

We are enabling a consistent, free to use, open source, and multi-chain compatible rarity ranking system that includes all of our EVM chains and Solana.

3/ To take a step back: when creators opted-in to @openrarity ranking, they tended to stay opted-in. To date, over 90% of collections remain opted-in.

With so much adoption already, it’s important now to build awareness and ensure that our community understands this methodology.

2/ The most consistent feedback the OpenSea team has received around OpenRarity from creators is “how do I get access?” 
Many creators didn’t realize that this functionality exists and, as a result, we’ve had an inconsistent buying and selling experience across collections.

We want to share an update on OpenSea’s rarity ranking: 
On Tuesday, Oct 25, we will adopt the @openrarity ranking methodology for eligible collections across all chains. This is a meaningful change and we want to share our rationale & next steps. 🧵⤵️ https://t.co/eq51Z4w7Gh

13/ Doing better begins w/ sharing & listening more. We’re committed to improving at both. Thank you for your feedback, your patience & your passion. Behind this blue boat is a group of humans who love this space like you do & we wouldn't be here without you. More from us soon 💙

12/ We care DEEPLY about enabling users to operate safely on our platform. Allowing the sale of stolen items and operating with stolen goods is no sign of a healthy ecosystem...but neither is a lack of trust from those of you who got us here.

11/ Take @MetaMask: they’re already doing meaningful work to help make users aware of what they are signing:  

https://t.co/D1z2um8vEL
10/ Beyond that, we are collaborating closely with ecosystem partners to help prevent and disincentivize theft, and building better education resources to help users stay safe in web3.

9/ In the long term, our key focus areas continue to be on finding solutions that tackle this problem at its root. Efforts are already underway to better automate threat and theft detection, such as blocking suspect URLs earlier.

8/ 2nd, we’re making it easier for users who reported an item stolen to re-enable buying and selling when they recover the item OR determine they should withdraw their stolen item report. For example, we're finalizing details on a simplified process that doesn't require a notary.

7/ For all reports going forward, if we don't receive a police report within 7 days, we’ll re-enable buying & selling for the reported item. This change will help prevent false reports. We think this is a good 1st step & we’re grateful for the community’s suggestions.

6/ Based on your input, we’ve already made the call to adjust elements of how we implement our policy. 1st, we're expanding the ways we use police reports: we've always used them for escalated disputes, but they'll now be used to confirm all theft reports.

5/ In some cases, the purchaser who unknowingly bought a stolen item (at no fault of their own) was inadvertently penalized. This is one of the most difficult issues we face. Please believe we take it seriously & we’ve been actively listening to your feedback on how to tackle it

4/ So why do we have this policy? It is against US law to knowingly allow the sale and transfer of stolen items. We do not want to incentivize theft by allowing our platform to be used to help sell stolen items.
3/ We're in this together: as we work to make our users safer, it's on us to keep you in the know.

2/ Our policy is designed to keep our community safe, but we know in some cases its side effects have damaged your trust in our platform. We’ve failed to proactively and transparently communicate the rationale behind our approach.

8/ We try to put the community first as we continue developing our Solana marketplace, and that’s why we do not custody your listings. Have the best of both worlds when you list on OpenSea. https://t.co/fbaqRBbFJp
7/ Also, if the marketplace goes down then your NFT may no longer be accessible…

6/ This practice also limits your security choices. When you list, your NFT leaves your wallet and is held by the marketplace’s smart contract. As a result you lose the ability to choose how or where your NFT is secured.
5/ For example, if you owned a Degenerate Ape, you couldn't list it for sale and continue to access the academy, the Discord, or show your friends your Ape in your wallet.

4/ When you have to give custody of your NFTs to a marketplace, you are forced to forfeit ownership. 

The NFT leaves your wallet and you can no longer benefit from ownership even before your item has sold.

3/ We believe marketplaces that custody your NFTs limit choice and utility, and compromise security.

Who benefits from custodying? The marketplace.

2/ Marketplaces should not require taking ownership of your NFT in order to list it for sale. 

This practice is more common with Solana NFTs. While some marketplaces require sellers to custody their listed NFTs, OpenSea does not. Here’s why ↯

This is one of many steps we’re taking to combat new scams and theft techniques, as soon as we see them emerging. As always, we welcome your feedback on these efforts!

We’re rolling out these changes today; but we’ll train our detection logic in the next several weeks. 

During this time, we may accidentally auto-hide legit transfers. If that happens – don't worry. It’s safe to unhide transfers you were expecting.

Today, we’re making three changes to protect you from suspicious NFT transfers:

1) Some transfers will now go to your Hidden folder, automatically. 
2) We'll periodically notify you when you receive a hidden transfer. 
3) Your Hidden folder now has new filter options.

The openness of the blockchain can bring unwelcomed activity – including unexpected NFT transfers from people you don’t know, similar to email.

Lately, we’ve seen some bad actors try to weaponize this feature to entice victims to visit malicious third-party websites.

Trust & Safety are core areas of focus for us at OpenSea. 

Today we’re rolling out our newest feature that automatically hides suspicious NFT transfers from view on OpenSea.

@Beetlearts Hi - please fear not! As we mention in our blog post, this is just our starting point (we have to dial up our new process slowly). To start, we'll invite accounts to apply that own a collection with >100 ETH of volume – but we’ll lower the floor & expand our criteria ASAP!

We'll start to invite accounts that own a collection with at least 100 ETH of volume to apply, and we’ll continue to expand eligibility criteria. 

Our goal is to eventually allow any authentic creator to be verified. There’s a lot more work to do, and this is just the start.

Verification on OpenSea aims to help both creators and collectors by surfacing authentic accounts and content more prominently. These changes will make it easier to do that moving forward. 

Accounts that are currently verified will not lose their status as part of these changes.

TLDR: we’re rolling out 4 changes to improve verification

1- Invite-based account verification with broader eligibility criteria
2- Updated collection badge
3- A new streamlined, in-product application
4- Dedicated customer support team for verification, with response in 7 days

After an immense amount of community feedback, contribution and support, we’re excited to roll out our new verification process. 

In this post, you will find more info on the changes and improvements we’ve implemented: https://t.co/k5JU3IghYv
This is just another step in our commitment to protecting our community, and building more trust in the NFT space. As always, we welcome your feedback, suggestions, and ideas.

2 - Reducing copymints: we’re rolling out an automated system to proactively identify, remove, and prevent copymints. 

More about this process here:  https://t.co/uokl7hTEe8

1 - We’ve updated our verification system to include an account verification and collection badging system, and we’re broadening the number of creators eligible for verification. 

More info to come on the new process in a separate thread.

Today’s announcement covers two areas: 

1 - Updating our approach to verification 
2 - Reducing copymints, or copies of authentic NFT content, on OpenSea

Imitation and plagiarism are growing issues in the world of NFTs. 

Today, we’re rolling out changes aimed at improving authenticity and reducing copymints on OpenSea.

We’re looking forward to welcoming a wave of new Solana projects onto OpenSea!
If you’ve migrated already, you can navigate to your page following these instructions (https://t.co/s58iPzS2P0) and start making changes.

For existing Solana projects: You’ll need to use this codeless tool (https://t.co/OnvvxVspvo) to migrate your project to the latest version. Once you’ve migrated, your collection will appear on OpenSea automatically.
For all new Solana projects: Using MCC lends authenticity to your project. You can specify this on CMv2 at time of creation or use this tool right after: https://t.co/OnvvxVspvo

What is MCC? 

Simply put, MCC is a way for creators to specify that a Solana NFT belongs to a specific collection on-chain. The added layer of on-chain specification will help prevent fraud and scams, on top of our existing trust & safety measures.

Big news for Solana creators: we now support @metaplex Certified Collections (MCC) in our Solana beta! Any collection that adopts MCC will now automatically appear on OpenSea with a clean, shoppable collection page. And 1k+ existing MCC collections are now live. 🎉

Collections that are already verified will have a reasonable grace period (e.g. 1 month) to complete the new verification steps to keep their status.
We are also exploring connected account ownership via oAuth to help prevent bad actors from copying legitimate collections.
We are planning to still require a minimum trading threshold, as we believe this is will help separate legitimate collections from copies.
We plan to allow creators to securely connect to accounts they own (e.g. Twitter and Discord) so the community can validate that those connections are authentic.

We are designing a new system to automatically verify collections that meet specific criteria. We will share these criteria openly with the community — but in the meantime, here’s a bit more about our plans...

Collection verification is an important signal for our community: it helps point to the authenticity of a given collection. But our current verification process hasn’t scaled with our business — it’s manual and slow, and we understand your frustration.

▫️ Join us

NFTs represent a new renaissance in the consumer internet, and it’s the perfect time to join the OpenSea team. If you’re interested in a role, we’re hiring across the board. https://t.co/zWmkXsDnWp

▫️ We want to hear from you

If you have suggestions for features that will benefit the community, let us know – we’re always up for hearing ideas on how we can improve the platform!

▫️ Homepage top collections

Art isn’t about money, but it’s sometimes fun to check the numbers. We added the top collections to the homepage to save you the click to the rankings page. (You can still head to the rankings page for all your filtering needs, of course!). https://t.co/7StKkuxgoj

▫️ Checkout warning about recently changed prices 

We're always coming up with ways to combat scammers based on what we’re seeing and feedback from the community.

We added a warning in the checkout flow if the price of an NFT has recently been changed. Better safe than sorry. https://t.co/J7JOQojWHM

▫️ Placeholder images for pre-reveal collections

It’s now clearer which items are pre-reveal and which ones aren’t. Why the computer face, you might be wondering? Why not? https://t.co/50sf0QbI0N

▫️ Creator addresses on collection pages

You can now see the creator account on collection pages under the collection name. We’re doing all we can to keep users safe in this brave new world. https://t.co/axHRwGWy5e

▫️ Activity page updates

The activity page is now accessible via the collection page and we made it easier to access key info! https://t.co/3ozWYRe3Ic

▫️ New collection review pop-up

We updated the warning pop-up for those clicking the buy button on unreviewed collections. Be careful out there, folks, and always do your research before confirming a purchase. https://t.co/NONDCd0MEM

▫️ Night mode is easier to find than ever

The video explains it better than we ever could.

For those wondering, the floating sky human shown in the recording is part of the Urban Anomalies collection by @ben_zank, and you can find it here: https://t.co/NFsSR9ITgQ https://t.co/hpJbWpFBQf

▫️ OpenSea partners with Adobe

If you didn’t catch the news when we announced it in October, our partnership with @Adobe represents an exciting step forward for user safety in the NFT space.

Read all about it: https://t.co/f6N11U3KJO https://t.co/FC9LdJC4Zj

New features & updates!

- @Adobe integration
- User safety improvements
- Collection & activity page redesigns
- Night mode accessibility 

And much, much more...

@bowsersbigDADDY This is a rundown of improvements from the last month or so! Plenty more to come.

⏲️ Floor price updates now real-time

The heading covers it. The floor price stat now updates in real-time, so no more waiting around.

Keep your eyes peeled for some more stats-related improvements coming real soon.

⏳ Status page

The new status page displays system metrics and the operational standing of the website, mobile app, and API.

If you notice an issue with OpenSea, check the status page for updates, and be sure that we’re working on it!

The page: https://t.co/EUL9CnNpW1

🎁 Gifted NFTs hidden by default

NFTs sent to you from unverified collections will now be located in the hidden tab on your profile. This will not apply to items from verified collections.

This is live on Polygon & Klaytn now, & we’ll be adding it for Ethereum-based NFTs soon.

💸 Royalty info at checkout

Buyers can now more easily view the royalty percentage that goes to the original creator before purchasing an item. https://t.co/V3qssm7vA3

🦋 Profile page improvements

The updated OpenSea profile header now makes it easier (and prettier) to associate your OpenSea account with your Twitter, Instagram, and website. https://t.co/vbul7OnXGW

🦺 Account safety

In the interest of protecting users from phishing attacks and other forms of theft, we’ve rolled out a feature that allows users to disable buying and selling for NFTs in their accounts.

To use it, head to 'Settings', then 'Account Support'.

🔧 Better offer management tools

We updated the listing flow and added some hotly-requested email-minimizing offer management features to make selling NFTs easier than ever.

✔️ Counter-offers
✔️ Minimum offers

Read all about it: https://t.co/ugm5yPO1BN https://t.co/TGQMAUOFf4

If it seems too good to be true, it probably is.

Sadly, there are bad actors looking to take advantage of those new to the world of NFTs. If someone offers you something that looks too good to be true, it probably is.

Avoid cold emails and downloading files from strangers.

It’s best to not interact with emails, files, and QR codes sent by strangers. Attachments of all formats, including PDFs, have been known to contain harmful viruses or malware.

Limit smart contract approvals.

If you're using MetaMask, make sure to review your spending limit when approving transactions. Click “Edit on Permission” and customize the spend limit for each currency.

For more context, check out this thread: https://t.co/gmJe6Fr75l

Use a crypto hardware wallet.

Using a hardware wallet adds another layer of security for your funds and NFTs. Many users tend to go with Ledger or Trezor.

Use Two-Factor Authentication (2FA).

Enable two-factor authentication with apps like Google Authenticator and Authy, and avoid SMS 2FA where possible since it can be vulnerable to attacks.

Never reuse passwords.

Reusing the same password across multiple accounts makes you more vulnerable to account compromises. A password generator or manager like 1Password or LastPass can make life easier if you’re worried about getting lost in a web of special characters.

Never click on unknown or broken links.

Stay vigilant when browsing websites and interacting with others on social media or Discord. Avoid clicking on ads, images, or links sent by strangers.

Make sure your wallet app or extension is the official one.

If you’re downloading a wallet browser extension, make sure to get your link directly from the provider’s website. When downloading an app, check the reviews and developer info to confirm you’re getting the right one.

Never share your secret recovery phrase.

Your wallet’s secret recovery phrase is private to you and should never be shared, even with those you trust. OpenSea is not a wallet provider and will never ask for your wallet’s secret recovery phrase.

Get support via official channels.

Customer support is never as fast as we want it to be, but soliciting help on social channels or Discord, where OpenSea does not provide official customer support, can make you a target for scammers.

We are working closely with the likes of Discord, Instagram, Facebook, and Twitter to ensure we are doing everything possible to mitigate risks for our growing community.

6. Never share your secret recovery phrase (seed phrase).

It's always worth saying again.

5. Report malicious behavior.

If you receive a DM and you have reason to believe it's an impersonator, research the reporting process and have them removed from the platform.

4. DYOR.

Always be cautious and perform due diligence where possible. If something seems too good to be true, it probably is.

3. Get support through Zendesk.

This is the only way to get support from the OpenSea team. We're rapidly hiring new agents because offering first-in-class customer service is a key goal.

To report fraud, pick the 'Trust & Safety' category.

Link: https://t.co/NQ5imyjdA3

2. Don't scan QR codes or click links you don't recognize.

Bad actors will impersonate OpenSea staff, build trust, then ask you to click something when your guard is down.

Stay vigilant.

1. Turn off Discord DMs on the OpenSea server.

Right-click on the server logo in Discord, press 'Privacy Settings', then disable direct messages.

Alternatively, turn off DMs globally by heading to your user settings. This will mean DMs are switched off on all your servers.

We're always taking steps to ensure our users feel safe.

We will never DM your first, ask for your seed phrase, request that you scan a QR code, or invite you to join a group chat or server that isn't linked to on our site.

💙 Join us

NFTs represent a new renaissance in the consumer internet, and it’s the perfect time to join the OpenSea team. If you’re interested in a role, we’re hiring across the board. https://t.co/zWmkXsDnWp

🙏 We want to hear from you

If you have suggestions for features that will benefit the community, reach out to us on Discord or Twitter – we’re always up for hearing ideas on how we can improve the platform! https://t.co/65hfFbNX7g

🛑 User safety 

In the interest of further reducing fraud on the platform, we now show verified checkmarks on asset cards for verified projects (along with a few other icons indicating asset properties). https://t.co/pYkSAu81jh

🎨 Collections

We’ve updated collection pages to show all items, and added filters and a search bar to make browsing easier than ever. Creators can also manage and add NFTs to their collections through a new admin panel at the top of the page. https://t.co/GTRFzVYHZH

💳 Credit & debit cards

As part of the ongoing roll-out of our gas-free marketplace, users can now purchase Polygon assets with credit and debit cards on OpenSea*.

*Not available in all US states and jurisdictions. https://t.co/eby5ffYikI

💸 Floor prices

Floor prices, a hotly requested feature, are now shown in each collection’s stats section for all the OpenSea power users out there.

This figure represents the lowest price any NFT in a particular collection is available for and is updated by the hour. https://t.co/glGIDmOixo

💁 Profiles

Profiles now have a new sidebar and a ‘Created’ tab showing NFTs an artist has made on OpenSea, Foundation, Rarible, their own smart contract, and other marketplaces we track. https://t.co/rrKtALaezt

📊 Rankings

The rankings page has been in for a facelift, and you can now filter by chain, floor price, and other metrics. https://t.co/rNXFl5pIfa

⚙️ New features & updates

July was a busy one. We doubled our monthly sales volume record, announced our Series B fundraising round, and added several new community-requested features to the platform.

Hurts to see friends in the space losing funds and NFTs.

Always be cautious and never open .scr files sent by strangers.

For tips and info on what to look out for, check out the user safety thread below. 

If it seems too good to be true, it likely is.

3⃣DYOR

If it seems too good to be true, it probably is. When buying NFTs, research the provenance of the items and be wary if the price looks low. If the creator hasn't publicly promoted the collection, reach out to them before purchasing.

Article: https://t.co/HBK8JvnMz6

4⃣Use the tools available

Take advantage of tools that facilitate trustless trades. If you agree to a sale on social channels, you can avoid fees by using OpenSea’s Private Sale option. Sending someone an NFT because they promised to send the funds is always a risk.

3⃣Check your numbers

When selling NFTs, check the price before finalizing listings and accepting offers.

2⃣Be vigilant

If you’re having trouble, request support via official channels. If someone you don’t know reaches out to you offering help, be careful not to click the links they provide and never share your seed phrase.

1⃣Be cautious

Check your wallet provider’s website for tips on looking after your seed phrase and password, and consider using a secondary wallet to store valuable items and funds.
